external.description: The developers have released Terminal-Bench 2.0 and Harbor, tools to address challenges in testing and optimizing autonomous AI agents. Terminal-Bench 2.0 offers a more rigorous and verified set of tasks for evaluating frontier model capabilities in realistic terminal environments. Harbor is a new framework that enables scalable evaluation of AI agents within containerized environments. It integrates with various agents and training pipelines, allowing large-scale testing across thousands of cloud containers. The developers stated Harbor is a tool they wished they had during Terminal-Bench's development. Terminal-Bench 1.0 was widely adopted but faced issues with poorly specified or unstable tasks. Version 2.0 directly addresses these by manually and LLM-assisted validating 89 tasks for realism and clarity. Harbor supports scalable supervised fine-tuning and reinforcement learning pipelines, and custom benchmark creation. Early results on the Terminal-Bench 2.0 leaderboard show OpenAI's Codex CLI, powered by GPT-5, leading with a 49.6% success rate. The close results among top agents highlight intense competition, with no single agent solving over half the tasks. Users can test or submit agents using Harbor with simple CLI commands, and submissions require multiple benchmark runs for validation. This dual release aims to establish standardization and a unified evaluation stack for the growing field of AI agents.
